posts.com:
Personally, I have to say that I never had much time for King Crimson. I disliked their first album and, apart from a track here and there, didn't find much I cared for on later albums either. To make things harder, they were contemporaries of Henry Cow and we were often pointlessly compared with them (especially Fred Frith who got foolishly compared/confused with Robert Fripp). But we never saw the connection really; they were working in a much narrower musical field than we were. And when they began to make big statements about their originality for improvising (around Jaimie Muir/Larks Tongues time) we found that frankly rather pathetic. But that was their way - after all Fripp claimed to have invented 'frippertronics', which is either a mark of ignorance on his part or outrageous arrogance, since every guitarist 'invented' that obvious procedure. I was not a fan of the other groups you list either, or Yes or Genesis for that matter, the quintessential 'progressive' groups. I don't think we had much in common with any of them. We certainly didn't learn anything from them. I, for instance, would have to go back to early Zappa, Beefheart, Barrett's Pink Floyd, Soft Machine, AMM, Sun Ra, Coltrane, Coleman, Stockhausen, Schoenberg and so on for influences. And for contemporary bands in the 70's, Magma, Faust, Samla Mammas Manna.

-Chris Cutler

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114723211
Metallica stopped being called power metal when other terms like thrash metal were coined and it became clear that their style was distinctly different from groups like Jag Panzer or Satan's Host or Brocas Helm.
The term power metal still stuck with these latter bands despite not really sounding much like their European counterparts because

>>114726909
I really can't jive with most of their music after the third album. Ditching the psychedelic sound and Jimbo's goofy beat poetry turned out to be a huge loss of personality for the band. What's left is just a competent but uninteresting bar band whose attempt at straight blues rock is lame as hell, and Morrison doesn't even sound like he's conscious or sober half the time. It's the sound of a band struggling to change with the times and realizing that they couldn't.
Morrison Hotel and LA Woman really don't hold up as full albums and the only compelling parts are when they briefly rekindle that early magic on tracks like Peace Frog and Riders on the Storm. They're one of the few bands where going "back to basics" was an artistic setback.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114730103
>the point is it is dated
It isn't, unless it tries as hard as possible to be innovative or "new". Music is not some sort of gadget that gets dated after several years. Music, at its ideal shape, is art. Art will never be dated. Purely entertainment products will be dated since they belong to a very particular era. Truly good music doesn't belong to any particular period and it will always have something to offer. Think of the harpsichord. People thought it's an outdated instrument when pianos became popular, but more and more people used them in the 60's and today it's another instrument having a very particular sound that is ought to be used, give the proper circumstances.
This is really what defines good from bad music: the power to be outside of time, to not sound dated. The most efficient way to achieve that is by accepting and by knowing the past and taking whatever sounds like it would work. To chase innovation will only result, paradoxically, in a creation that's simply a product of its time, a novely, a failed experimet that brings innovation, eventually, but it's not innovative in itself. The 80's showed everyone this: all the new, exciting innovations, like the Fairlight, E-mu, Linn Drum or the DX7, sound so stereotypically 80's, that everyone can tell it belongs to that era. On the other hand, take Gentle Giant: they were not afraid to have medieval or Baroque influences in their music and the music sounds as fresh as ever, merely because it doesn't try to be new, but it tries to be as good as possible.
>any appreciation of it is inherently nostalgic in nature
It really isn't. I don't listen to Captain Beefheart because I'm nostalgic or I have a sense of nostalgia, I listen to his music because there's barely anything sounds quite like that and I really enjoy the music. Even if there might be, I rather listen to the one that came out with such music first. I don't care it came out in 1969 since I have no appreciation of that era.

>>114730103
>>114730276
I don't miss anything from the past, I just look at things that I can enjoy or offer some sort of answers to my questions. That's pretty much how it's happening in every single discipline: you build up towards the future based on the already existent knowledge so that you'll have more knowledge. Why does music has to be any different?
>You can still appreciate the original 1930s Frankenstein movie, which I do very much, but it will always be done through the lens of HINDSIGHT
That's a rather faulty example. If we think of today's films as nothing but special effects and pure fiction, yeah, Frankenstein is a very primitive form. But you don't have to make new films full of special effects. You don't have to make films about fictive creatures. You can make a slice of life. You can make a comedy. A drama and so forth. You might learn to use shades quite like they did in noir films, but in a modern setting or use a similar aesthetic to 40's films right now. There's no reason to limit the methods one can use in order to create.
>Music evolves, you should evolve with it.
Music evolves, but it's not a simple, linear line. Think of punk and the whole post punk musicians. They pretty much used the 50's to come up with something new. That's innovation, as opposed to some synth nerd using the latest Moog to noodle around some chromatic scales. The way peole evolve is also not linear. You come back and forth between various states of mind and this friction makes you evolve, not the pure movement towards a perceived point of absolute evolution. I always find new things I like, but I won't torture myself to listen to the newest shit possible just because it's new. The so called past has a lot more to offer, at least for now. I might come up with new things and that's enough for me. Show me a rock band today using Messiaen's modes of limited transposition. Or spectral music influences. All of these are new. I don't need anyone to paint my own future.

French here. Objectively: 3rd place.
We are big in the underground free party scene, we invented frenchcore and our DJs are/were the biggest in the tribe genre. We have "French touch" electro house, some of our DJs are big like Justice or French 79. And obviously we have Laurent Garnier, Jean-Michel Jarre, Daft Punk, David Guetta, ...
2nd place: Germany. True techno, some incredible artists, with the Berlin scene.
1st place: the UK. They invented most of the techno we listen to: acid, trance, drum and bass, the list could go on.
Honorable mentions: the US, because that's where techno came from and good DJs come from there but they were surpassed by Europe. The Netherlands are also similar to Germany but they don't bring new things to the table, they just have excellent DJs (and gabber).

>>114729789
Peace In Your Heart
intro - I6/9 (6 and 9 in guitar melody)
v - Imaj | % | II-7 | II- (V7) | I6/9 | % |

The next few verses he embellishes the II- to V with the "minor line cliche", changing the phrase to II- II-maj7 II-7 V7. Somewhere in there he switches to I VI- II- V, III- VI7, II- V I, I VI- I VI- etc. etc.

Not trying to give you anything exact since he's erratic anyway but this basically demonstrates Charlie's familiarity with 20th century popular harmony. These are basically jazz or 50's/60's pop changes. Charles Manson had some degree of familiarity with music theory given these progression which contain modal interchange and secondary dominant chords.

Retard here again. I can't wrap my head around time signatures. I understand that the first number is the number of beats and the second is whether it's half quarter or eight beats but wtf?
Does that mean 4/4 is downstrum only and if you're doing 1&2&3&4& it's 4/8?
My brain hurts.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114728537
numerator is how many beats are in a measure
denominator is what division is counted as a beat
4/4 has 4 beats in a measure with each beat being a quarter (1/4) note
3/4 has 3 beats in a measure with each being a quarter note
6/8 has 6 beats in a measure and each beat is an eighth (1/8) note
and so on and so forth
however you've decided to count subdivisions does not affect the time signature
You would count 4 beats of 4/4 as 1 2 3 4
You would count 6 beats of 6/8 as 1 2 3 4 5 6

The guitar also needs to have an arched top like a Les Paul or its difficult to angle the bow just so it only bows one or two strings at a time.
